        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "`@.github/workflows/e2e.yml` is set up for a Windows machine that GitHub can dispatch jobs to, but because these tests drive a real Visual Studio UI, the runner needs an interactive desktop session, not just a background service.\n\n## Recommended Setup\n\n1. Prepare a dedicated Windows 11 VM or physical machine.\n2. Install:\n- Visual Studio 2022 `17.12+`\n- WebView2 Runtime\n- Git\n- .NET SDK\n- Anything your normal build already needs for `make build`\n\nFor Visual Studio, make sure `devenv.exe` and `VSIXInstaller.exe` are present. Installing the `Visual Studio extension development` workload is the safest choice.\n\n3. Add the GitHub Actions runner:\n- Go to your repo: `Settings -> Actions -> Runners -> New self-hosted runner`\n- Choose `Windows` / `x64`\n- Download and extract the runner\n- Run `config.cmd`\n\nExample:\n\n```powershell\n.\\config.cmd --url https://github.com/<org>/<repo> --token <registration-token>\n```\n\n4. Keep the default labels.\nThat workflow uses:\n\n```yaml\nruns-on:\n  - self-hosted\n  - windows\n  - x64\n```\n\nThose labels are normally added automatically.\n\n## Important: Run It Interactively\n\nFor UI automation, do **not** rely on the runner as a Windows service.\n\nInstead, run the runner in a logged-in desktop session:\n\n```powershell\n.\\run.cmd\n```\n\nBest options:\n- dedicated user account, always logged in\n- start runner at logon via Task Scheduler\n- disable sleep/screensaver/auto-lock\n\nIf the desktop is locked, many UI automation tests will fail.\n\n## Recommended Machine Settings\n\n- Power mode: never sleep\n- Disable automatic reboots during working hours\n- Keep one logged-in desktop session alive\n- Avoid using the machine for anything else during e2e runs\n\nIf you connect over RDP, disconnect carefully. Some UI automation stacks break when the session gets minimized/locked. A common workaround is using `tscon` to hand the session back to the console instead of just closing RDP.\n\n## Repo Secrets\n\nThis workflow also expects:\n\n- `CODESCENE_IDE_DOCS_AND_WEBVIEW_TOKEN`\n\nAdd that under:\n\n- `Settings -> Secrets and variables -> Actions`\n\n## Smoke Check\n\nOnce the runner is online:\n\n1. Confirm it appears under repo runners as `Idle`\n2. Trigger `.github/workflows/e2e.yml` with `workflow_dispatch`\n3. Verify these steps succeed:\n- asset fetch\n- `copy-assets.ps1`\n- solution build\n- `.github/e2e.ps1`\n- artifact upload\n\n## Practical Recommendation\n\nUse a dedicated VM just for this workflow. It makes flaky UI issues much easier to control and debug.\n\nIf you want, I can give you:\n1. a concrete Task Scheduler setup so the runner starts at login, or\n2. a checklist of exact Visual Studio components to install for this repo.",
