          "text": "Here’s a concise answer and what was added in code.\n\n### Can you avoid it programmatically?\n\n**There’s no supported `devenv` switch** that turns off that Copilot onboarding screen. Practical options:\n\n1. **Machine policy (most reliable)**  \n   Use the Visual Studio **Administrative Templates (ADMX)** and disable Copilot under **Computer Configuration → Administrative Templates → Visual Studio → Copilot Settings** (including **Copilot Free** from 17.13+). That stops the modal without touching your tests.  \n   [Admin controls for GitHub Copilot in Visual Studio](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/visualstudio/ide/visual-studio-github-copilot-admin?view=visualstudio)\n\n2. **Runner hygiene**  \n   Uninstall or disable the GitHub Copilot extension on the **e2e-only** VM so it never loads in `/RootSuffix Exp`.\n\n3. **UI automation in the harness (what we implemented)**  \n   After VS starts, the host now runs **`DismissKnownBlockingDialogs()`** (from `WaitForShellStabilization`): it looks for **“Maybe later”** (invoke pattern or click) and, if needed, a top-level window whose name contains **“Copilot”** and tries the **Close** button.  \n   - Opt out with: **`CODESCENE_E2E_SKIP_COPILOT_DISMISS=1`**  \n   - It stops polling after a short stretch with no dialog so normal runs don’t wait 45 seconds when Copilot isn’t there.\n\nAlso fixed **`devenv /updateconfiguration`** success check to **`Assert.AreEqual(0, exitCode, ...)`** (the previous `IsLessThanOrEqualTo(0, exitCode)` was wrong).\n\n**Docs:** [E2E-TESTING.md](E2E-TESTING.md) now describes Copilot, the env var, and Group Policy.\n\nIf “Maybe later” is not exposed as a single UIA element on your build (e.g. only a text run), say what Inspect/Accessibility shows and we can narrow the condition (e.g. parent hyperlink / automation id).",
